						               													<description>De Verbis is a promotional word-formation game from Linguam&amp;oacute;n - House of languages and it can be played in various languages. From the rules booklet:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;        &amp;quot;Only one thing is more fun than guessing words: getting others to do it. In DE VERBIS, players take turns at thinking up and guessing words. The player who does it best wins the round.&amp;quot;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Contents:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     45 letter cards&amp;#10;     10 &amp;quot;?&amp;quot; cards&amp;#10;     30 counters&amp;#10;     A pen and paper are needed for keeping score&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Summary of rules:&amp;#10;In each round one of the players thinks a 8-10 letter word and marks it with the &amp;quot;?&amp;quot; cards on the table and keeps the deck of letter cards. The other players are given some tokens and, in turn, they ask for a letter: if it is included in the word, the player with the deck of cards places that letter in its correct position on top of the corresponding &amp;quot;?&amp;quot; card; if the letter is not in the word, the player who asked for it must pay 1 token. Whenever a player guesses the word correctly he receives 2 tokens plus as many tokens as &amp;quot;?&amp;quot; cards are still in the word; but if the guessed word is wrong, the player must pay 2 tokens. The player who thought the word receives as many tokens as the difference between the top scorer and the least scorer.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Following the philosophy of the publisher the rules are in Catalan, Spanish, English, French, Basque, Galician, Occitan and Italian.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;About the publisher:&amp;#10;The publisher, Linguam&amp;oacute;n &amp;ndash; House of Languages, is a body set up by the Government of Catalonia with the aim of promoting the world's languages as a:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     vehicle for communication, civilization and dialog &amp;#10;     source of personal development, human creativity and heritage of mankind &amp;#10;     right of individuals and of linguistic communities&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
